sp id="CR1"><bold>Corresponding author:</bold> Andrea S. Young, PhD, Division of Child and Adolescent Psychiatry, Johns Hopkins School of Medicine, 1800 Orleans Street, Bloomberg 12 N, Baltimore, MD 21287</corresp></author-notes><pub-date pub-type="ppub"><day>01</day><month>12</month><year>2023</year></pub-date><pub-date pub-type="epub"><day>08</day><month>6</month><year>2023</year></pub-date><volume>74</volume><issue>12</issue><issue-id pub-id-type="pmc-issue-id">458924</issue-id><fpage>1218</fpage><lpage>1226</lpage><pub-history><event event-type="nihms-submitted"><date><day>22</day><month>03</month><year>2024</year></date></event><event event-type="pmc-release"><date><day>01</day><month>12</month><year>2024</year></date></event><event event-type="pmc-live"><date><day>01</day><month>12</month><year>2024</year></date></event><event event-type="pmc-last-change"><date iso-8601-date="2024-12-01 00:25:14.133"><day>01</day><month>12</month><year>2024</year></date></event></pub-history><self-uri xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" content-type="pmc-pdf" xlink:href="nihms-1977151.pdf"/><abstract id="ABS1"><sec id="S1"><title>Objective:</title><p id="P1">An expert consensus approach determined adequacy of children&#8217;s psychopharmacology, examining whether adequacy varied by demographic and/or clinical characteristics.</p></sec><sec id="S2"><title>Methods:</title><p id="P2">Data were from the baseline interview of 601 6&#8211;12-year-olds who had visited one of nine outpatient mental health clinics and participated in the Longitudinal Assessment of Manic Symptoms (LAMS) study. Children and parents were interviewed using the Kiddie Schedule for Affective Disorders and Schizophrenia and the Service Assessment for Children and Adolescents to assess youths&#8217; psychiatric symptoms and lifetime mental health services use, respectively. Analyses employed an expert consensus approach (informed by published treatment guidelines) to determine children&#8217;s psychotropic medication treatment adequacy.</p></sec><sec id="S3"><title>Results:</title><p id="P3">Black youths (compared to white youths; OR=1.84, 95% CI=1.53&#8211;2.23), those with anxiety disorders (vs. no anxiety disorder, OR=1.55, 95% CI=1.08&#8211;2.20), and those whose caregivers had a high school education, GED or fewer years of education (vs. those who had a bachelor&#8217;s or more advanced degree, OR=0.74, 95% CI=0.61&#8211;0.89) were more likely to receive inadequate pharmacotherapy.</p></sec><sec id="S4"><title>Conclusions:</title><p id="P4">Using the consensus rater approach permitted use of published treatment efficacy data and patient characteristics (e.g., age, diagnoses, history of recent hospitalization, psychotherapy) to assess adequacy of mental health treatment. These results replicate racial disparities found in previous research using traditional methods to determine treatment adequacy (e.g., with a minimum number of treatment sessions) and highlight the continued need for research on racial disparities and strategies to improve access to high quality care.</p></sec></abstract><kwd-group><kwd>children</kwd><kwd>mental health services</kwd><kwd>mental health care disparities</kwd><kwd>psychopharmacology</kwd></kwd-group><custom-meta-group><custom-meta><meta-name>pmc-status-qastatus</meta-name><meta-value>0</meta-value></custom-meta><custom-meta><meta-name>pmc-status-live</meta-name><meta-value>yes</meta-value></custom-meta><custom-meta><meta-name>pmc-status-embargo</meta-name><meta-value>no</meta-value></custom-meta><custom-meta><meta-name>pmc-status-released</meta-name><meta-value>yes</meta-value></custom-meta><custom-meta><meta-name>pmc-prop-open-access</meta-name><meta-value>no</meta-value></custom-meta><custom-meta><meta-name>pmc-prop-olf</meta-name><meta-value>no</meta-value></custom-meta><custom-meta><meta-name>pmc-prop-manuscript</meta-name><meta-value>yes</meta-value></custom-meta><custom-meta><meta-name>pmc-prop-legally-suppressed</meta-name